The Cygnus Loop (also known as the Veil Nebula) is a supernova remnant, left over from a massive stellar explosion that occurred 5,000 to 8,000 years ago. The original supernova would have been bright enough to be seen clearly from Earth with the naked eye. At three degrees across, the Cygnus Loop is as wide as six full moons in the night sky.

This image is a combination of X-ray data from NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory and optical data by amateur astronomer John Stone ‚Äî but the @NASAChandraXray team has also just released a new 3D visualization of the Cygnus Loop. It visualizes how the blast wave from the explosion interacts with an isolated cloud of the interstellar medium (that is, dust and gas in between the stars). You can view that 3D model and others like it at nasa.gov/chandra.

Image description: In the composite image, the remnant resembles a wispy cloud in oranges, blues, purples, and whites, shaped like a backwards letter C. The remnant is set against a backdrop of scattered stars.

Apollo 16 astronauts John W. Young and Charles M. Duke drove the lunar rover to Plum Crater on April 21, 1972, to collect samples; this photo of Duke was taken by Young, the mission commander. "Big Muley," a 26-pound (11.7-kg) rock collected by Young and Duke on the rim of Plum Crater, was the largest single sample brought back from the Moon during the entire Apollo program. 

Today, we're preparing for #Artemis II, which will send humans around the Moon in 2026 for the first time in over 50 years. Follow @NASAArtemis for the latest mission updates!

caption:
Add a pop of color! üé®‚Å£
 ‚Å£
When the cameras on NASA‚Äôs New Horizons spacecraft first spotted the large reddish polar region on Pluto‚Äôs largest moon, Charon, mission scientists knew two things: they‚Äôd never seen anything like it elsewhere in our solar system, and they couldn‚Äôt wait to get the story behind it.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Turns out Pluto is something of a graffiti artist ‚Äì methane gas escapes from Pluto‚Äôs atmosphere, becomes ‚Äútrapped‚Äù by Charon‚Äôs gravity, and freezes to the cold, icy surface at the moon‚Äôs pole. When it‚Äôs springtime on Charon, the returning sunlight triggers the frozen methane to change back into gas, which leaves behind heavier chemical compounds. Sunlight further irradiates those leftovers into reddish material that has slowly accumulated on Charon‚Äôs poles over millions of years.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
The image combines blue, red, and infrared images taken by New Horizons‚Äô Ralph/Multispectral Visual Imaging Camera (MVIC); the colors are processed to best highlight the variation of surface properties across Charon. New Horizons was the first spacecraft to explore Pluto up close. In early 2019, New Horizons flew past its second major science target ‚Äì Arrokoth, the most distant object ever explored up close.‚Å£

Image description: Pluto‚Äôs largest moon, Charon, is gray with a jagged line of fractures and canyons going across it diagonally. There are many craters visible, especially on the bottom and right sides. At the top, in a region informally named Mordor Macula, Charon is a deep, rusty red.‚Å£

caption:
That‚Äôs one speedy spud ü•î‚Å£
‚Å£
@NASAHubble took 13 separate exposures over 22 minutes to create this time-lapse image of tiny, potato-shaped moon Phobos (at left) orbiting around Mars. Phobos is so small that it looks like a star in these Hubble photos.‚Å£
‚Å£
This little tater is fast, though: Phobos orbits Mars in just 7 hours and 39 minutes, which is faster than Mars rotates. The moon‚Äôs orbit is very slowly shrinking, meaning it will eventually ‚Äì as in, 50 million years from now ‚Äì break up under Mars‚Äô gravitational pull, or crash onto the planet.‚Å£
‚Å£
Poor little Phobos has already been battered: it was nearly shattered by a giant impact, and has gouges from thousands of meteorite impacts.‚Å£
‚Å£
Here are a few more fun facts about Phobos:‚Å£
- It has no atmosphere.‚Å£
- It‚Äôs the larger of Mars‚Äô two moons. The other moon is called Deimos.‚Å£
- The fine dust on Phobos‚Äô surface cannot retain heat.‚Å£
‚Å£
Image description: Tiny moon Phobos travels behind Mars in this image. The moon appears multiple times, since this is a time-lapse photo. Phobos is a small silvery dot here. Mars dominates the photos. Mars is mostly red-orange, with dark blotches and silvery wisps all around its edges.‚Å£

This understanding is enhanced when art, science, and microgravity come together. 

Check out a few of Don‚Äôs many photos.

Image descriptions: 
1. Comet C2024-G3 soars through space as pictured from the ISS. The lower half of the photo glows blue from Earth‚Äôs atmosphere; the top half contrasts with the blackness of space. 2. 3. A time-lapse image of an aurora dancing over Earth. The aurora glows in shades of green and diffuses in the atmosphere in red hues. City lights shine through the aurora in white.

caption:
Livin' life in low Earth orbit 

For nearly 25 years, @NASAAstronauts have been living and working aboard the International Space Station. Some have only stayed for a few days, while some have lived in space for over a year at a time. (Astronaut Frank Rubio holds the NASA record, with a 371-day stay.) Some have traveled to the @ISS several times, while some are making their first visit‚Äîlike NASA's Nichole Ayers, seen here opening the hatch to the station's Kibo laboratory. Ayers launched to the station on NASA's SpaceX Crew-10 mission, which lifted off from @NASAKennedy on March 14.

The International Space Station is an orbiting laboratory, built to help us learn how to live in space while making life better back on Earth. We work with crew members and researchers from around the world to study human health, medicine and biology, materials research, Earth science and countless other scientific disciplines. (Visit nasa.gov/iss-research for more info.) Now, we're working with commercial partners on a new generation of space stations, making space more accessible and affordable as we send humans to the Moon and Mars.

Image description: Astronaut Nichole Ayers floats above a large, circular hatch in the International Space Station. She is looking down at the hatch and wearing a crimson long-sleeved shirt; her blond hair floats above her head. The hatch is hinged open to reveal the circular doorway into the station's Kibo laboratory; behind her, the walls of the station are mostly white panels, with a few cords and pieces of hardware.

caption:
For 20 years, @NASAHubble has been studying Uranus... and learning more about its gas.

Uranus' atmosphere is mostly hydrogen and helium, with a small amount of methane‚Äîbut that methane gives Uranus its distinctive cyan color. Our orbiting Hubble telescope studied Uranus between 2002 and 2022 and found that unlike other gas giants, Uranus has much less methane near its poles. 

Hubble also tracked complex circulation patterns in the planet's atmosphere, giving scientists a deeper look into Uranus.

This classic image of Uranus was taken not by Hubble, but by NASA's Voyager 2 spacecraft as it flew by the planet on Jan. 14, 1986.

caption:
View from a lifeboat

Apollo 13 astronauts Jim Lovell, Fred Haise, and Jack Swigert launched from @NASAKennedy on April 11, 1970. They were headed to the Fra Mauro region of the Moon for the third lunar landing ever. Everything seemed to be going smoothly until the third day of the mission, when an oxygen tank ruptured and Swigert uttered those famous words: ‚ÄúHouston, we‚Äôve had a problem here.‚Äù

The new mission plan was to abandon the Moon landing, loop around the Moon, and get the crew home safely as quickly as possible. The crew needed to go into ‚Äúlifeboat mode,‚Äù using the lunar module Aquarius to save the spacecraft and crew. The Apollo 13 crew took this photo of the Moon from the lunar module as they passed by.

On April 17, the crew returned to Earth, splashing down in the Pacific Ocean near Samoa. The Apollo 13 mission is sometimes called a ‚Äúsuccessful failure‚Äù: Though the crew couldn‚Äôt achieve their scientific goals, the rescue mission was a huge victory for NASA. The lessons learned from Apollo 13 were rapidly applied to the remaining Apollo missions and continue to guide us at NASA today.

Image description: The Moon‚Äôs gray, cratered surface is visible from the Apollo 13 lunar module. To the right, the shut-down command module covers some of the view. There are marks that look like plus signs overlaid on the photo.

caption:
Can we get an encore?

A planetary nebula located just 4,600 light-years away in the Milky Way galaxy puts on a spectacular display at the end of a giant star's life. The image itself was the final work of one of @NASAHubble's instruments: the Wide Field and Planetary Camera 2 (WFPC2). First installed in 1993, the WFPC2 was replaced in 2009 by the Wide Field Camera 3 during Hubble‚Äôs final servicing mission.

The swirling, paint-like clouds in the darkness of space are clouds of ionized atoms thrown into space by a dying star. Its red giant star had exhausted its available fuel and shed its last layers of gas, enabling nuclear fusion as its compact core begins to contract further. The exposed core reaches extremely hot temperatures, radiating ultraviolet light that energizes the enormous clouds of gas cast off by the star. 

In this image, red and orange indicate nitrogen, green is hydrogen, and blue shows oxygen. The spectacle is bittersweet, as the brief phase of fusion in the core will end after only tens of thousands of years, leaving a white dwarf that will never illuminate the clouds around it again.

Image description: A glowing, jagged ring encircles a small central region of greenish clouds, making it appear like a hole torn in fabric. This ‚Äúhole‚Äù is itself encircled by a band of silvery-blue clouds and a larger, fainter, yellow ring of gas. Puffy, smoky clouds of orange and red gas billow out from there into a large oval nebula, fading into the dark background of space dotted by stars.

Credit: @EuropeanSpaceAgency/Hubble & NASA, K. Noll

On February 7, 1984, astronaut Bruce McCandless II became the first human in history to go on a spacewalk without a connection to their spacecraft. McCandless soared outside the space shuttle Challenger with the Manned Maneuvering Unit (MMU), a propulsion device on the back of his spacesuit that used two tanks of hydrogen and 24 nozzles to move him around. 

In this iconic photo, taken by Challenger pilot Hoot Gibson, McCandless was just a few meters away from the shuttle, but further MMU flights by McCandless and astronaut Robert L. Stewart took them more than 300 feet (91 meters) into space. The MMU was used for several more flights in the 1980s. Today's @NASAAstronauts now wear SAFER (Simplified Aid For EVA Rescue), a smaller, simpler thruster system, in case they accidentally become untethered on a spacewalk.

Earth's blue seas and thin white clouds arc over the bottom half of this image; the astronaut is just above Earth's curvature. From the perspective of the photograph, he is leaning approximately 45 degrees to the right.

Status: It‚Äôs complicated.‚Å£

@NASAWebb captures a rare cosmic phenomenon in this new image, called an Einstein ring. What may look like one strangely-shaped galaxy is actually two galaxies separated by a large distance. The closer galaxy sits at the center of the image, while the more distant background galaxy appears to be wrapped around the closer galaxy, forming a ring.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Now, stay with us here ‚Äî the light from the more distant galaxy is being bent (or lensed) by the closer, massive galaxy. This is possible because spacetime, the fabric of the universe itself, is bent by mass. Therefore, the light traveling through space and time is bent, as well. While too subtle to observe on smaller scales, the astronomical proportions allow us to observe the curvature of light.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Only at the perfect alignment ‚Äî between the lensed object and the lensing object ‚Äî can this distinctive Einstein ring shape be seen.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Image description: In the center is an elliptical galaxy, seen as an oval-shaped glow around a small bright core. Around this is wrapped a broad band of light, appearing like a spiral galaxy stretched and warped into a ring, with bright blue lines drawn through it where the spiral arms have been stretched into circles. A few distant objects are visible around the ring on a black background.‚Å£

About 5,550 light-years away in our galaxy, there‚Äôs a magical light show going on. Also, X-rays can penetrate the shrouds of gas and dust surrounding these infant stars, allowing astronomers to see how stars are formed with details that would be otherwise missed.‚Å£

@NASAWebb treated us to a sweet perspective: Herbig-Haro 49/50‚Äîa towering swirl from a nearby protostar‚Äîis (coincidentally) topped with a multi-hued spiral galaxy.‚Å£
‚Å£
Herbig-Haro objects are outflows produced by jets launched from a nearby, forming star. The outflows, which can extend for light-years, plow into a denser region of material. This creates shock waves, heating the material to higher temperatures. The material then cools by emitting light at visible and infrared wavelengths.‚Å£
‚Å£
The galaxy that appears, by chance, at the tip of this cosmic soft-serve is a much more distant, face-on spiral galaxy. It has a prominent central bulge represented in blue, filled with older stars. The bulge also shows hints of ‚Äúside lobes,‚Äù suggesting that this could be a barred spiral galaxy. Reddish clumps within the spiral arms show the locations of warm dust and groups of forming stars.‚Å£
‚Å£
Image description: This cosmic image is dominated with billowing clouds of orange-red gas, rich in detail. At the tip of the cloud, a spiral galaxy is visible, with a concentrated blue center that fades outwards to blend in with red spiral arms. caption:
See some supersonic shockwaves üëÄ
 
You're looking at two T-38 jets, soaring faster than the speed of sound‚Äîflying in formation just 30 feet (9 meters) apart. This image was taken using a technique called schlieren photography, which measures the flow of air around objects. When an aircraft goes supersonic (about 760 miles an hour, or 1220 kph, at sea level), it sends shockwaves through the air, rapid pressure changes which are responsible for the sonic boom you may hear on the ground.
 
This photo was taken by a @NASA aircraft in 2019‚Äîthe first flight ever to capture interacting shockwaves from two supersonic aircraft. Images like these are helping us design our @NASAAero X-59 aircraft, which aims to fly at supersonic speeds without creating loud sonic booms. X-59 is currently gearing up for its first flight later this year.
 
Image description: Two jet planes, seen from below, fly through a bright blue background. Dark lines, indicating the path of their shockwaves, extend at trailing angles from the jets, with bright red trails visible very close to the jets. This image was originally monochromatic and is shown here as a colorized composite.
 
Credit: NASA

Your screen isn't fuzzy‚Äîyou're looking at planets 130 light-years away.

Exoplanets, or planets beyond our solar system, are so small that we usually detect them by measuring the effect they have on their star: they may cause the star to wobble a bit, or make it a little less bright as they pass in front of it. But our @NASAWebb telescope is so powerful that it can spot, not just distant stars, but the much smaller worlds that orbit them. 

The HR 8799 star system has long been of interest to astronomers for what it can tell us about how planets form, and Webb is giving us a better look at it than ever. Not only are we getting a direct look at these four gas giants, Webb's data tells us that these worlds are rich in carbon dioxide, suggesting that they formed similarly to Jupiter and Saturn in our home system.

At the center, the star HR 8799 is denoted by a white, five-pointed star graphic.

caption:
What lies beneath‚Å£
 ‚Å£
In this image, Venus may look like a serene planet, with white and tan clouds reminding us of a cozy cup of coffee. In reality, Venus is a world of intense heat, crushing atmospheric pressure, and clouds of corrosive acid.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
The clouds seen here are comprised of sulfuric acid particles, as opposed to water droplets or ice crystals like on Earth. On top of being made of corrosive acid, these Venusian clouds whip around the planet at nearly over 200 mph (322 kph), circling the planet in about four and a half days.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
So far, we‚Äôve got acidic clouds and hurricane-force winds. Underneath the clouds lies extreme heat and pressure: Venus is hotter even than the innermost planet, Mercury. Venus‚Äô thick atmosphere traps heat in a runaway greenhouse effect, giving it surface temperatures hot enough to melt lead! Finally, the surface pressure on Venus is 92 times that of Earth‚Äôs. To experience that pressure on our home planet, you‚Äôd have to dive more than 3,000 feet (915 m) into the ocean.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
So why do we study this seeming hellscape of a planet? Although it‚Äôs not currently habitable, Venus lies within the Sun‚Äôs "Goldilocks zone," and may have been habitable before Earth. We want to understand how Venus became an inferno-like world when it has so many other characteristics similar to ours. Future missions like DAVINCI, VERITAS, and EnVision will seek to answer this question.‚Å£
 ‚Å£

Our Voyager 1 spacecraft took this iconic image of Earth 35 years ago. Voyager 1 was so far away ‚Äî 3.7 billion miles (6 billion km) ‚Äî from the Sun that, from its vantage point, Earth was just a point of light about a pixel in size. Truly a ‚ÄúPale Blue Dot.‚Äù‚Å£‚Å£

Mission managers commanded the spacecraft to look back toward home for a final time. It snapped a series of 60 images that were used to create the first ‚Äúfamily portrait‚Äù of our solar system.‚Å£‚Å£

Carl Sagan was a prominent planetary scientist who was a consultant and adviser to NASA beginning in the 1950s. He also was a member of the Voyager Imaging Team. ‚Å£‚Å£
After snapping the Pale Blue Dot and other ‚Äúfamily photos,‚Äù Voyager 1 powered off its cameras forever to save its energy for the long journey ahead. In August 2012, Voyager 1 entered interstellar space. It‚Äôs now the most distant human-made object ever.‚Å£‚Å£

caption:
Black Holes: Cooked. Ate. Left no crumbs.
 
Recent studies show that black holes in the universe can create their own meals. Data from our @nasachandraxray Observatory and the Very Large Telescope (VLT) provide new evidence that outbursts from black holes can help cool down gas to feed themselves.
 
The centers of galaxy clusters contain the universe‚Äôs most massive galaxies, which harbor huge black holes with masses ranging from millions to tens of billions of times that of the Sun. Jets from these black holes are driven by the black holes feasting on gas.
 
The latest research supports a model where outbursts from the black holes trigger hot gas to cool and form narrow filaments of warm gas. Some of the warm gas in these filaments should then flow into the centers of the galaxies to feed the black holes, causing an outburst. The outburst causes more gas to cool and feed the black holes, leading to further outbursts - a cosmic buffet!
 
Image descriptions: A swipe-through of different galaxy clusters, each with a central black hole surrounded by patches and filaments of gas. In each image, a patch of purple with neon pink veins floats in the blackness of space, surrounded by flecks of light. At the center of each patch is a glowing, bright white dot. The bright white dots represent black holes. The purple patches represent hot X-ray gas, and the neon pink veins represent filaments of warm gas.
 
In the image of the Perseus Cluster on the left, the surrounding flecks of light are larger and brighter, making the individual galaxies they represent easier to discern. The purple gas has a blue tint, and the hot pink filaments appear solid, as if rendered with quivering strokes of a paintbrush. The Centaurus Cluster is on the right; in this image, the purple gas appears softer, with a more diffuse quality. The filaments are rendered in more detail, with feathery edges, and range in color from pale pink to neon red.
 
Credit: (X-ray:) ASA/CXC/SAO/V. Olivares et al.; Optical/IR: DSS; H-alpha: CFHT/SITELLE; Centaurus Cluster: (X-ray:) ASA/CXC/SAO/V. Olivaresi et al.; (Optical/IR:) ASA/ESA/STScI; H-alpha: ESO/VLT/MUSE; Image Processing: NASA/CXC/SAO/N. Wolk

caption:
Stars hatched by a swan üåü

Our WISE telescope captured this image, released in June 2011, of a huge complex of star-forming clouds and stellar clusters in the constellation Cygnus. Star clusters are groups of stars that share an origin, forming at roughly the same time and location, and are tied together by gravity for up to millions or even billions of years.

Different types of stars have different life spans, so clusters will change over time as stars evolve. Some clusters might contain big, hot, O-type stars. Others might hold smaller, cooler stars that age and change over billions of years. Star clusters can contain anywhere from as few as a dozen stars to upwards of millions, and those stars can be spread out over a few light-years to hundreds of light-years.

WISE (Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer) was an infrared-wavelength astronomical space telescope. It was placed into hibernation in February 2011, having completed its primary astrophysics mission. Then, in 2013, the spacecraft was assigned a new mission as NEOWISE (Near-Earth Object Wide-Field Infrared Survey Explorer), to help find near-Earth asteroids and comets. Its mission ended on July 31, 2024.

Image description: This image is dominated by curving green clouds, except at top left and middle, where there are also red clouds. A few bright yellow stars shine through the most defined clouds. There are also tiny multicolored ‚Äì though mostly blue ‚Äì dots of light throughout the whole area.

Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/UCLA

caption:
Keep your eye on the donut and not on the hole.

Released in 2019, this is the first image of a black hole and its shadow, which represents a historic feat by an international network of radio telescopes called the Event Horizon Telescope (EHT). A black hole is an extremely dense object from which no light can escape. Anything that comes within a black hole‚Äôs ‚Äúevent horizon,‚Äù its point of no return, will be consumed, never to re-emerge, because of the black hole‚Äôs unimaginably strong gravity. Not unlike the Black Lodge.

In this image, you can see the shadow of the supermassive black hole in the center of Messier 87 (M87), an elliptical galaxy some 55 million light-years from Earth. This black hole is 6.5 billion times the mass of the Sun. Catching its shadow involved eight ground-based radio telescopes around the globe, operating together as if they were one telescope the size of our entire planet.

In memory of David Lynch, we will continue to explore the otherworldly and the unknown. We will focus not on the loss, but on what we gained from the years we shared this planet with you. We will see you in our dreams.

Image description: Using the Event Horizon Telescope, scientists obtained this image of the black hole at the center of galaxy M87, outlined by emission from hot gas swirling around it under the influence of strong gravity near its event horizon. The hot gas is shaped like a doughnut and is glowing a warm yellow color with reddish tint at its edges. The darkness of space is black in the background.

Credit: Event Horizon Telescope collaboration et al.

caption:
Shooting for the stars... üåü 

NASA astronaut Jeanette Epps used her unique vantage point aboard the @ISS to capture the perfect shot: a long-exposure photo of Earth as stars glittered above the atmosphere. 

Setting the camera‚Äôs light sensitivity (ISO) to 3200‚Äîa higher sensitivity used to capture more detailed images in low-light conditions‚ÄîEpps positioned her lens in one of the space station‚Äôs many windows and clicked the shutter. What resulted 68 seconds later was a stunning portrait showcasing streaks of city lights across Western Australia, with swirls of stars above Earth‚Äôs golden-red atmosphere. 

Photographs like this show just how quickly the space station‚Äîand astronauts aboard‚Äîmoves as it orbits our home planet: a whopping 17,500 miles per hour (28,000 kph). It also gives our @NASAAstronauts novel opportunities to try out new camera techniques that may just result in a spectacular view for us to enjoy here on Earth as well. 

Image description: In the bottom half of this image, displayed over two slides, Earth glows in hues of gold as a red atmospheric glow curves above. Yellow city lights streak across Earth horizontally, as star trails create a circular pattern in motion directly above. 

Credit: NASA/Jeanette Epps

Out of the dozens of moons that orbit Saturn, the one that‚Äôs closest to the gas giant is Mimas, first discovered in 1789 by English astronomer William Herschel. Mimas is about 115,000 miles (186,000 km) from Saturn‚Äîhalf the distance from the Earth to the Moon‚Äîand takes just 22.5 hours to make a lap around the giant planet. 

Mimas can be seen at the very bottom of this image, which was taken by our Cassini spacecraft in 2005. Behind it, Saturn‚Äôs northern latitudes shine in a cool blue, with shadows from its rings forming long, dark lines on the atmosphere. 

Image description: The surface of Saturn takes up most of this image, with thin, dark lines arcing down and to the right over a periwinkle-colored atmosphere. At the very bottom, just left of center, the moon Mimas appears as a gray, slightly dimpled circle. 

Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/Space Science Institute

caption:
Multiple fires have been burning in Los Angeles County since early January. Smoke plumes from the fires can be seen over the Pacific Ocean from space, visible in this @NOAA-20 satellite image from Jan. 9. Powerful Santa Ana winds and a lack of rain created ‚Äúcritical‚Äù fire weather conditions in Southern California, according to the @nws, contributing to the rapid spread of the fires.
 
As of Jan. 10, the Palisades Fire in California has burned nearly 20,000 acres. This fire, along with many others in the area, have forced evacuations in and around the Los Angeles area, including our @NASAJPL facility. Historically, California‚Äôs fire season runs from June or July through October or early November. The hot, dry conditions that drive fire season are now present longer into the winter, fueled by a warmer climate. NASA just confirmed 2024 was the hottest year on record.
 
We continue to think of all our colleagues, friends, and first responders affected by the fires during this time.
 
Credit: NOAA-20 Satellite
 
Image description: Satellite image of southern California on Jan. 9, 2025. The land is mostly shades of tan and brown, with small patches of dark green vegetation in the northern part of the image. The lower left third of the image is dark blue ocean water. Large plumes of whitish gray smoke are streaming out over the water from the Palisades and Eaton Fires in the region. The further south smoke plume is larger and reaches further over the water.

caption:
That‚Äôs no Moon‚Ä¶‚Å£
‚Å£
Because it‚Äôs Mercury! No one would blame you for mistaking one for the other, though. The two bodies do have some visual similarities: Mercury is only slightly larger than our Moon, and they‚Äôre both gray and cratered. NASA‚Äôs MESSENGER spacecraft captured this visible and infrared light view of the planet on Jan. 14, 2008, about 80 minutes before it made its closest pass at a distance of about 17,000 miles (27,000 kilometers). MESSENGER would go on to conduct two more flybys of Mercury on Oct. 6, 2008, and Sept. 29, 2009.‚Å£
‚Å£
MESSENGER ‚Äì which stands for Mercury Surface, Space Environment, Geochemistry and Ranging ‚Äì was the first spacecraft to orbit Mercury. Its primary goal was to study the geology, magnetic field, and chemical composition of the planet. It was the first mission to Mercury after Mariner 10, more than 30 years before.‚Å£
‚Å£
One of the first things MESSENGER discovered was high concentrations of magnesium and calcium on Mercury‚Äôs night side. It also found large amounts of water in the outermost layer of Mercury‚Äôs atmosphere and revealed evidence of past volcanic activity on the surface.‚Å£
‚Å£
The spacecraft completed its primary mission on March 17, 2012, having taken nearly 100,000 images of the surface of Mercury.‚Å£
‚Å£
Image description: Mercury looks almost like a waning crescent moon in this image. About three-quarters of the planet are in the frame, with only a thin slice of it lit. The bright part stands out starkly against the darkness of space.‚Å£
‚Å£
Credit: NASA/Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory/Carnegie Institution of Washington‚Å£
‚Å£

caption:
New moon before the new year
 
The new moon begins on Dec. 30, 2024, when the illuminated side of the Moon faces the Sun and the night side faces Earth. This long-duration photograph, taken with a camera programmed with high sensitivity, shows an astronaut's perspective during a new moon phase on Sept. 4, 2024, as the Moon set behind Earth's colorful, but dimming atmosphere.
 
For astronauts on the International Space Station (@ISS), the Moon appears to rise and set 16 times per day, as the station orbits Earth about every 90 minutes.
 
Image description: A new moon with a sliver of the edge illuminated appears behind the edge of Earth's atmosphere, during moonset, and soon to be hidden behind Earth. The atmosphere is blue, with orange and yellow hues below.
 
Credit: NASA/Matt Dominick

caption:
Even as a star dies, its light endures‚Äîechoing across the cosmos.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
The James Webb Space Telescope is giving astronomers an unprecedented look at the fine details and 3D structure of the dust and gas between the stars.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
The space between the stars is not empty, but rather filled with filaments of dust and gas (known as the interstellar medium), which is often invisible until something illuminates it.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Here, a long-ago supernova explosion, acting like a flashbulb, has heated some of this interstellar material, causing it to glow in the infrared, creating a thermal ‚Äúlight echo.‚Äù‚Å£
 ‚Å£
As the supernova illumination travels through space at the speed of light, the echo appears to expand. Click the link in @NASAWebb‚Äôs bio to read more and to see more images and a video showing the change over time.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
The structures in these filaments are on a remarkably small scale of about 400 astronomical units, or less than one-hundredth of a light-year. (An astronomical unit, or AU, is the average Earth-Sun distance and is equal to 93 million miles or 150 million kilometers.)‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Credit: NASA, ESA, CSA, STScI, J. Jencson (Caltech/IPAC)‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Image descriptions: Two frames show an infrared light echo traveling from the lower left of the first image through the upper right of the second image. They are not perfectly contiguous due to how the data were collected. Each image is speckled with dozens of white stars, some showing Webb‚Äôs signature 8-point diffraction spikes, against the black background of space. The images also show tightly packed, glowing red filaments that resemble muscle fibers or wood grain.‚Å£
 ‚Å£

caption:
Sometimes you‚Äôve got to bloom before you glow. üåü 

...just like this rare Wolf-Rayet star did before going supernova. 15,000 light years away from the constellation Sagittarius, WR 124 shed its outer layers, resulting in halos of gas and dust that appear like a blooming flower‚Äîa fleeting phase that happens to only some stars before they explode. 

In this composite image from @NASAChandraXray, @NASAWebb and WISE, WR 124 gleams as dozens of other bright stars surround it. X-rays from Chandra are colorized purple, while infrared frequencies captured from WISE are blue. Observations from Webb‚Äôs Near-Infrared and Mid-Infrared instruments are red, green, and blue. 

The star itself is 30 times the mass of our Sun and has shed 10 Suns‚Äô worth of material so far. As the gas moves away and cools, cosmic dust forms, showering astronomers with a deeper insight into a crucial period in the early history of our universe. Stars similar to WR 124 first seeded the young universe with heavy elements forged in their cores ‚Äì elements that are now common in the universe‚Äôs current season, including on Earth. 

Image description: A large eight-pointed star shines at the center of the image in white and blue hues. This month has it all: planetary cameos, appearances from distant stars, and the winter triangle. Tune in to hear what‚Äôs up for December.
 
Planet Visibility
Mercury: Visible very low in the southeast just before sunrise during the last half of the month.
Venus: Shines brightly as the "Evening Star" in the southwest after sunset, climbing higher each evening.
Mars: Brightens significantly during December, rising in the east-northeast and visible from late evening to early morning.
Jupiter: Reaches opposition on Dec. 7, making it visible all night, rising in the east-northeast.
Saturn: Visible after sunset in the southern sky, shifting slightly westward as the month progresses.
 
Highlights
Dec. 3-5 ‚Äì Venus and the Moon: Look southwest after sunset to see a beautiful pairing. On Dec. 4, a slim crescent Moon will sit directly below Venus.
Dec. 7 ‚Äì Jupiter at Opposition: Jupiter will shine at its brightest for the year, rising in the east-northeast among Taurus's stars. Best viewed through a telescope for details like the Galilean moons and atmospheric belts.
Dec. 14 ‚Äì Jupiter, the Moon, and Aldebaran: Look for Jupiter midway between the nearly full Moon and bright orange star Aldebaran in the evening sky.
Dec. 17 ‚Äì Mars and the Moon: Mars, glowing brightly in its approach to opposition, appears super close to the waning gibbous Moon.
All Month ‚Äì Winter Triangle: Formed by Sirius, Procyon, and Betelgeuse, this asterism marks the arrival of winter skies and is a prominent feature throughout the season.
Dec. 13-14 ‚Äì Geminid Meteor Shower: The peak occurs under a nearly full Moon, reducing visibility, but bright meteors may still be spotted the week before.
Dec. 21 ‚Äì Winter Solstice: At 4:20 a.m. EST, the solstice marks the beginning of winter in the Northern Hemisphere and summer in the Southern Hemisphere.
